WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.040
provide also the basis for deepening of economic integration in other fields.

00:05.280 --> 00:11.000
Second environment, it was emphasized that the EU and Russia have a lot of fundamental

00:11.520 --> 00:17.060
interests in common in this field and much can be done also on the basis of the

00:17.060 --> 00:23.420
existing international agreement and especially in the framework of the Nordic Dimension, the CFSP.

00:24.360 --> 00:30.640
Third and last is armament. This could become a field of growing importance for

00:30.640 --> 00:38.260
bilateral cooperation also in view of the EU declared intention to become more active

00:38.260 --> 00:42.380
in dealing with the problem of the spread of weapons of mass destruction.

00:43.340 --> 00:51.300
A final word, several participants have emphasized that quite important bridging role

00:51.300 --> 00:58.620
can be played by the exceeding countries, the new member states, in view of strengthening

00:58.620 --> 01:05.980
of EU-Russia cooperation by means of the links they have developed with Russia in the last decades.

01:06.560 --> 01:07.340
Thanks.

01:07.340 --> 01:21.620
Thank you very much, Latorre. I would like to ask if nobody is frustrated from these reports

01:21.620 --> 01:27.500
of the different working parties. That means if they forgot perhaps an important point

01:27.500 --> 01:35.100
which could have been discussed. Oh yes, but I will not open again the discussion about

01:35.100 --> 01:41.420
this substance. It's only a form, it's time to one short compliment.

01:47.500 --> 01:54.360
I just wanted to say that I never said that the southern countries are against democracy

01:54.360 --> 02:03.600
or human rights. I think all these countries have already signed and ratified all the instruments

02:03.600 --> 02:12.900
regarding to human rights. I just wanted to point out that democracy and human rights

02:12.900 --> 02:18.180
should not be a kind of blackmail for our countries. Thank you very much.

02:18.640 --> 02:29.000
Good. Well, I suppose that everybody agrees and I think my conclusion about these reports

02:29.000 --> 02:36.380
is that we were able to give an answer to the basic question raised yesterday by Alvaro

02:37.080 --> 02:48.420
Vasconcellos who was asking after the speeches of Mr. Amato and Elmar Brock if the convention

02:48.580 --> 02:58.920
was not too inward looking exercise from the side of the EU and if the convention didn't

02:58.920 --> 03:07.920
forget to think about the external identity. My impression after having heard these different

03:08.540 --> 03:16.200
comments on the different external issues is that we have no substance, not only formal

03:16.200 --> 03:23.420
decisions of the convention dealing with the decision making process, dealing with the

03:23.420 --> 03:35.480
formal issues, we have now enough materials to develop an external identity in the different

03:35.480 --> 03:43.940
fields which were approached this morning and which were very rich. I think it was also

03:43.940 --> 03:51.460
very rich dealing with the different suggestions to the Italian presidency, everybody talked

03:51.460 --> 04:00.360
about that and I think we are able to present now to this presidency a very rich program

04:00.360 --> 04:07.520
of initiatives in the different directions which were underlined in the exposés.

04:07.780 --> 04:14.720
I thank again the reporters, they had not a long time to prepare the report but they

04:14.720 --> 04:22.900
did extraordinarily well and thank you again for your reports.

04:24.320 --> 04:29.300
We will go over now to the second part of this and final part because it's already one

04:29.300 --> 04:40.680
o'clock and we have still half an hour before finishing and I'm happy to give in the first

04:40.680 --> 04:49.800
place the floor to President Lamberto Odini, former Prime Minister of Italy, thank you

04:49.800 --> 04:56.900
again very much for having accepted our invitation and we are happy to hear your comments.

04:57.160 --> 05:03.860
Well, thank you very much Mr. President. First I would like to congratulate Yai and

05:03.860 --> 05:12.220
Professor Bonvicini to have organized this meeting on a vast agenda and wide ranging

05:12.220 --> 05:21.340
discussions have taken place on so many subjects. Now Andrew Duff and myself have been members

05:21.770 --> 05:29.700
of the European Convention but since on the results of the Convention you heard yesterday

05:29.700 --> 05:37.720
Emma Brock and Giuliana Manto, I don't think we should enter into give our own judgment

05:37.720 --> 05:46.420
on how we came out according to our own vision of the future of Europe and I think that Andrew

05:46.420 --> 05:52.900
Duff and myself would want rather to look forward to the remaining work that the Convention

05:52.900 --> 05:59.420
can make in the coming two weeks actually starting next week on the fundamental questions

05:59.420 --> 06:09.400
of the policies including decision makings and what kind of criteria in decision making

06:09.400 --> 06:22.880
especially expanding to the extent possible the qualified majority voting and Andrew I

06:23.820 --> 06:32.540
listen with attention and the reports by the head of the groups, of the working groups

06:32.540 --> 06:40.400
on these four subjects. I would like to make only a few comments if you allow me Mr. Chairman

06:40.400 --> 06:47.080
both on the Mediterranean and especially the future of Iraq. I think there is less to

06:47.080 --> 06:57.380
say perhaps in terms of comments concerning the other two groups. Now it was said and I

06:57.380 --> 07:07.380
agree fully that the Barcelona process and the MEDA project should be revised, should

07:07.380 --> 07:15.240
be revived and perhaps revised in light of developments. I think that is to be done.

07:15.240 --> 07:22.900
We shouldn't forget that the Barcelona process main objective was to arrive at the free

07:22.900 --> 07:30.600
trade area with this country by the year 2010 and now we hear that the United States is

07:30.600 --> 07:38.300
expressed in the same view trying to organize in the course of time a free trade area for

07:38.300 --> 07:45.620
the Mediterranean and the Middle East countries again in 10 years time. Now we do not know

07:45.620 --> 07:53.580
what are the instruments that the United States intend to use to foster and this process

07:54.360 --> 08:01.760
because it has not been specified whereas we do know which are the means that the European

08:01.760 --> 08:10.020
Union has been using to try to bring about you know progress in the three different

08:10.020 --> 08:18.040
fields and economy, the political area and the social progress that would lead therefore

08:18.040 --> 08:29.160
also into the towards a free trade area by making these economies more competitive externally.

08:29.160 --> 08:40.380
But why the MEDA and the Barcelona process did not progress as much as desired. Now I think

08:40.380 --> 08:47.560
this may be a lesson to be useful also to the United States if it wants to help the

08:47.560 --> 08:54.700
Mediterranean countries in their economic and social development. Now first I think

08:54.700 --> 09:05.080
it is fair to say that the European Union has been slow in pushing forward the infrastructure

09:05.080 --> 09:15.020
projects using the same criteria for that are applied to member countries and the same

09:15.020 --> 09:24.340
demands, the same standards and that the European Union has required of member countries

09:24.340 --> 09:31.540
the same have tried to apply to the Mediterranean countries where of course the conditions are

09:31.540 --> 09:38.440
somewhat different. So there hasn't been much flexibility, the result is the gestation period

09:38.440 --> 09:46.540
for infrastructure project has been extremely long. Second in the Mediterranean countries

09:46.540 --> 10:00.200
there has always been let's say uneasiness on the expansion of NATO and also regional arrangements

10:00.200 --> 10:07.120
that the European Union has made, Euromar, Euro4 during the years I have been foreign minister

10:07.120 --> 10:13.280
have always been questioned and say why do you need all these arrangements? Why do you

10:13.280 --> 10:19.020
need all these defense kind of instruments? Aren't these going to be a sort of a threat

10:19.020 --> 10:29.160
vis-à-vis us? Now of course it is not but how to reassure these countries in this area

10:29.160 --> 10:36.620
which I think is now even more fundamental question after the action of the United States

10:36.620 --> 10:43.660
in Iraq, who is going to ensure security to the Mediterranean countries? We ought to think

10:43.660 --> 10:53.200
about this. Indeed as part of the Barcelona process we worked for several years, more

10:53.200 --> 11:00.860
than several years on a possible security agreement between the European Union and this

11:00.860 --> 11:08.920
country so as to assure them that through the dialogue consultations and so on, on developments

11:08.920 --> 11:18.920
of what Europe was doing that was not intended at all to constitute. So establishing better

11:18.920 --> 11:26.940
cooperation in this field leading to a security agreement that has never been materialized.

11:26.940 --> 11:34.380
Now this seems to me of a crucial question on security for these countries in the future.

11:35.200 --> 11:43.240
Beyond what we can do, you know, ourselves. Now in terms of social progress and try to increase

11:43.240 --> 11:50.620
and improve the understanding between these Mediterranean societies and European world,

11:50.620 --> 12:00.500
the European countries, we had launched the idea of a Mediterranean TV, television,

12:01.380 --> 12:08.940
in which there would be an exchange of programs between European programs that are devoted

12:08.940 --> 12:16.500
to that part of the world and also programs and ideas coming from them that could be integrated

12:16.500 --> 12:24.760
in Europe. Now also this project has not materialized. I must say that there were more fears

12:24.760 --> 12:30.540
on the part of some of the Mediterranean countries than on the part of the European countries

12:30.540 --> 12:40.520
because it would have meant for some of them to open up the kind of exposure to the public

12:40.520 --> 12:55.740
of ways, way of life and the things that our society develops, you know, in terms of culture

12:55.740 --> 13:03.600
in particular. So also these were the three reasons I think why the Barcelona process

13:03.600 --> 13:11.760
and MEDA did not progress as much. Therefore let's revive and revise the Barcelona process.

13:11.900 --> 13:17.540
I think that Europe can do much better in that part of the world in the Mediterranean

13:17.540 --> 13:25.080
down to the Middle East than any other area or any other country. I'm ready to bet on this

13:25.080 --> 13:31.140
that we can do much more for these countries in terms of bringing them closer.

13:32.000 --> 13:39.060
I heard about association agreements. I think Europe should work on cooperation agreements

13:39.060 --> 13:45.340
first of all. Some countries, Egypt and others, there is Tunisia, there is an association agreement

13:45.340 --> 13:54.360
but it has been, you know, it will take time to develop but also that should be encouraged.

13:56.720 --> 14:05.780
Now then policy for democratization of human rights, I think it has been said rightly,

14:05.780 --> 14:16.820
this is not an exportable goods and in particular we should be sensitive to the maintenance

14:16.820 --> 14:25.460
of regional stability and with economic growth will also the social and political development

14:25.460 --> 14:35.980
I think will occur and this on the Mediterranean this would have been my comments.

14:36.360 --> 14:43.100
Let's see in particular what the United States has in mind when he is proposing a free trade area

14:43.100 --> 14:51.620
with these countries from the year 2012. See whether the US is in a position to do better than Europe

14:51.620 --> 14:58.140
I doubt this but in any event let's hope that the United States also will make an effort

14:58.140 --> 15:10.340
as much as Europe in favor of these countries. Now on the future of Iraq, I think there is a request

15:10.340 --> 15:19.860
for a new European policy on Iraq and mention has been made to this excellent report by Solana

15:19.860 --> 15:32.740
on fighting terrorism and also preventive action linking up hopefully well with the United States.

15:33.440 --> 15:41.720
Now why it has not been possible so far to develop a single European policy on Iraq?

15:41.720 --> 15:51.460
And we know the shambles in which the European countries found themselves and I think aside from

15:51.460 --> 15:57.580
what has been said some countries may have had economic interest, I think that Europe

15:57.580 --> 16:05.720
and this is the matter that links up to the convention does not have today an adequate mechanism

16:05.720 --> 16:11.800
or an instrument, adequate and effective instrument for decision making.

16:12.680 --> 16:19.400
And this is the key question. It has been an intergovernmental matter, foreign policy

16:20.700 --> 16:31.320
and on which unanimity is required to say anything positive. I would like to say here once more

16:31.320 --> 16:37.020
and I have said it elsewhere that in the five years that I have been foreign minister we discussed

16:37.020 --> 16:45.920
the Middle East issue every month in the General Fair Council, it is to say the Council of Foreign Ministers.

16:46.780 --> 16:55.200
And we all agreed around the table that of course we should foster the peace process

16:55.200 --> 16:59.980
and being pleased to the region. But then when we started to decide

